<TEXT>
posters of him mark the entrance to every 
iraqi village radio and television broadcasts call him 
fatherleader even childrens nursery rhymes sing his praises 
iraqi president saddam hussein is the center of a powerful 
personality cult that hails him as a stern father an arab leader 
a warrior the last of those was in the forefront thursday with 
saddams rapid invasion of iraqs small persian gulf neighbor 
kuwait 
the effective ruler of iraq since 1968 saddam established a 
ruthless dictatorship his rule has brought the longest period of 
stability to iraq a coupplagued country created after world war i 
with a diverse population of shiite and sunni moslems christians 
and kurds 
saddam sees his carefully cultivated image as crucial to iraqi 
unity in a 1983 interview with kuwaiti journalists at a low 
point in iraqs bloody eightyear war with iran he said he must 
be a symbol of all iraqis 
iraqi poems incessantly praise saddam pictures of a smiling 
saddam are on posters everywhere and photos of him adorn the front 
page of every newspaper radio and television broadcasts call him 
fatherleader or knight of the arab nation 
an iraqigovernment advertisement in the new york times compared 
saddam to hammurabi the great king of babylon on the euphrates 
river who first codified laws nearly 4000 years ago 
the personality cult is backed up by a pervasive apparatus of 
oppression that included four police forces four intelligence 
services and according to human rights organizations the use of 
torture summary execution and imprisonment without legal process 
with frequent purges saddam took firm control of the army one 
former ruler had called a factory of coups it became a capital 
offense for an officer to be involved in any political activity 
other than functions of the ruling baath party 
after saddam came to power as strongman behind gen ahmed hasan 
albakr in 1968 about 50 high military and civilian officials were 
executed 
in 1982 amid widespread disappointment as iran drove the iraqis 
out of captured iranian territory there were two attempts to 
assassinate saddam another purge followed 
after the iraniraq war saddam brutally subdued rebellious 
kurdish guerrillas using chemical weapons against some kurdish 
settlements he created a depopulated strip along the borders with 
turkey and iran that cut kurdish fighters off from outside supplies 
intelligence reports indicate he has spent billions of dollars 
some estimates say 50 billion on arms chemical weaponry and 
testing of sophisticated artillery capable of lobbing 
nucleartipped artillery shells at enemies hundreds of miles away 
saddam and most of his ruling entourage are sunni moslems 
several from his hometown of tikrit he uses carrotandstick 
tactics to control the shiite moslems who form the majority of 
iraqs 17 million population the iranians are overwhelmingly 
shiite 
he spent lavish amounts of money to restore shiite shrines at 
najaf and karbala but when an iranianbacked shiite organization 
dawa or the call was formed to disrupt his rule he responded 
harshly in 1984 an estimated 600 members of dawa were executed 
in may 1983 he arrested 90 members of the prominent shiite 
family alhakim because one of them was making antiiraqi 
broadcasts from iran when the broadcasts continued he executed 
six members of the family in front of the others 
the war with iraq which iraq started in 1980 became part of 
saddams personality cult though it gained no territory or other 
advantage for iraq and stalled vigorous oilfueled economic 
development for eight years 
in the wars last battles iraqi forces drove iranians out of 
captured iraqi territory leading to the 1988 ceasefire the media 
refers to the struggle as saddams qadissiya a reference to a 
7thcentury victory of arabs over persians 
saddam was born april 28 1937 in tikrit 75 miles north of 
baghdad on the tigris river the son of a poor peasant at 20 he 
joined the thenunderground baath party 
his tough ambition and leadership qualities won him appointment 
to a baath team assigned to assassinate iraqs thenruler 
abdulkarim qassem in 1959 the squad sprayed qassems car with 
machine gun fire but he escaped saddam wounded in the leg also 
escaped 
his fearlessness having his wound operated on in a baghdad 
hideout his flight across desert to syria and then egypt are 
glorified in iraqi books and films 
he worked underground until the baaths seizure of power in 
1968 in 1979 he took full control from albakr 
from that year saddam has been president chairman of the 
council of ministers commanderinchief chairman of the 
revolutionary command council and leader of the iraqi wing of the 
baath party 
even before the kuwait invasion he flexed his muscles 
earlier this year saddam threatened to destroy half of israel 
with internationally outlawed chemical weapons if israel tried to 
attack any iraqi military facilities 
obsessed about security he ordered the march 15 execution of 
iranianborn londonbased journalist farzad bazoft who had tried 
to gather information about a massive explosion at a 
militaryindustrial complex outside baghdad 
