<TEXT>
here is a brief look at the history of iraq and kuwait 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
iraq part of the ottoman empire from the 16th century was 
captured by british forces in 1916 in 1921 it became a kingdom 
under a league of nations mandate administered by britain iraq 
became independent on july 14 1958 in a coup that established a 
militaryled council of sovereignty headed by gen qassim 
qassim was overthrown in 1963 and gen abdul salam aref became 
president succeeded by his brother abdul rahman aref in 1966 
in 1968 a successful coup brought by the baath party placed 
gen ahmed al bakr in power saddam hussein bakrs vice president 
since 1969 became president in 1979 in a peaceful transfer of 
power 
in 1980 iraq invaded iran in a territorial dispute over the 
shattalarab waterway that evolved into a nearly eightyear war a 
un ceasefire halted the fighting on aug 20 1988 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
kuwait became part of the ottoman empire in the 16th century 
during the later years of ottoman rule kuwait became a 
semiautonomous arab monarchy with local administration controlled 
by a sheikh of the sabah family which continues to be the ruling 
dynasty 
in 1899 fearing an extension of turkish control the ruler of 
kuwait made a treaty with the united kingdom accepting british 
protection while surrendering control over external relations the 
sheikhdom remained a selfgoverning british protectorate until it 
gained independence in 1961 
of all the gulf states kuwait has been most vullnerable to 
regional disruption immediately after independence british troops 
were called on to support the country against territorial claims by 
iraq the force remained until 1963 and relations between the 
countries were stable until 1973 when iraq occupied a kuwaiti 
outpost on their common border substantial donations to iraq 
subsequently ensured kuwaits territorial security 
continued financial aid to iraq during its war with iran and 
the protection of the united states for its oil tankers in the 
persian gulf kept kuwait relatively safe during the gulf war 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

