<TEXT>
federal agents in nightvision 
goggles prowled feathery marijuana patches in a federal invasion 
that has brought a panamatrained army unit and claims of civil 
rights violations to the mountains of northern california 
the national guard and bureau of land management took reporters 
on a helicopter tour thursday of the region 180 miles northeast of 
san francisco where government is conducting its largest drug raid 
ever on public lands 
it is also the first time the army has been used for a marijuana 
raid in the continental united states 
the army contingent includes seven helicopters and 58 aviators 
and maintenance personnel from the 7th infantry division the fort 
ordbased unit that saw action in the panama invasion last december 
officials wouldnt say if the pilots were the same who flew 
missions against deposed panamanian leader manuel noriega who 
surrendered to us troops in january and is on trial for drug 
charges in miami 
operation green sweep began sunday and will continue through 
next week in the king mountain range at the edge of the emerald 
triangle so dubbed because much emeraldcolored marijuana is 
grown in the region 
the king range is basically one big garden said craig 
macgill a blm agent in charge of ground operations officials 
offered no estimate at the value of the marijuana grown here but 
say it may be in the billions 
more than 200 troops and agents swept in by ground and air at 
the start of the surprise operation they sealed off a 640acre 
area near the city of garberville and civilian air traffic below 
5000 feet was barred in a surrounding 1200squaremile area 
macgill said 16 raids have turned up 14 gardens containing 682 
plants worth more than 2 million no growers have been arrested 
about 200 protesters blocked the gate to the operations base 
camp thursday and one of the protesters was arrested 
local law enforcement officials privately have said the 
involvement of the military was unnecessary humboldt sheriff dave 
renner has disassociated himself from the operation calling it 
illadvised and counterproductive 
blm director delos jamison the senior official present said 
the raid sends a message to marijuana growers and international 
allies in the drug war that the united states is serious 
some reports have said the bush administration which is 
pressuring bolivia peru and colombia to halt cultivation of coca 
plants in the andes is embarassed by the lush marijuana growth on 
its own public lands 
on thursday visitors were shown a plot containing about 20 
plants in a steep ravine where blm agents in full battle dress and 
camouflage paint stood guard with loaded assault weapons each of 
the plants had a street value of up to 3000 officials said 
maj gen robert thrasher the state national guard commander 
said federal agents and guard troops began hiding overnight 
wednesday around undisturbed gardens and used nightvision goggles 
in hopes of spotting the growers 
jamison discounted residents claims of being held at gunpoint 
by soldiers bearing m16 assault rifles and being buzzed at low 
altitudes by helicopters 
he questioned whether some of the protesters were actually pot 
growers 
i think the locals here that are really protesting maybe 
were pulling up some of their plants i dont know jamison said 
as part of the operation officials have removed trip wires 
intended as boobytraps to protect illegal gardens 
authorities said they plan to restore the forest to its pristine 
state removing the sophisticated drip and gravityflow irrigation 
systems some of them on batteryoperated timers set up by pot 
growers 
