nearly one in four american infants is born to an 
unmarried mother six times as many as four decades ago federal 
health officials say 
among black infants the rate is more than six in 10 the 
national centers for disease control reported thursday 
infant mortality rates are higher among children born to single 
mothers who often provide less financial security than some 
married parents the cdc said 
twentyfour percent of us infants were born to unmarried women 
in 1987 the latest year for which statistics are available the 
cdc said in 1950 the figure was 4 percent 
the percentage of black infants born to unmarried mothers was 62 
percent compared with 17 percent of white infants both are up 
from 1983 when 59 percent of black births were to single mothers 
compared with 13 percent of white births the cdc said 
these figures are alarming said evelyn lowery president of 
sclc women a branch of the southern christian leadership 
conference the problems are not getting better theyre getting 
worse 
