<TEXT>
consumer and business groups want to know why 
american telephone amp telegraph co apparently pocketed as much as 
200 million of a governmentordered 500 million price reduction 
last month but a regulator says the utility acted properly 
the groups on thursday petitioned the federal communications 
commission to consider rule changes that would require atampt to 
reveal how it figured that in response to an fcc order it had to 
cut prices only about 300 million rather than about 500 million 
fcc chairman alfred sikes told a house subcommittee that atampt 
has fully flowed through its share of access price decreases to 
its price caps 
he said atampt had dropped prices so much voluntarily before july 
1 that it needed only to reduce prices an additional 300 million 
an atampt corporate vice president tom norris labeled any 
allegations of impropriety as preposterous and said the company 
would fight any move to force it to disclose more information about 
its rate filings 
the petition was filed on the same day that democratic members 
of the house telecommunications subcommittee urged the fcc not to 
make a multibilliondollar mistake by too aggressively 
deregulating the longdistance marketplace 
at the subcommittee hearing sikes was asked to defend 
commission proposals to loosen further federal oversight of atampt 
and impose a new pricebased regulatory system on the interstate 
longdistance earnings of the nations local telephone companies 
lawmakers said they feared the fcc had not sufficiently studied 
recent changes in the longdistance business and the impact that a 
major deregulatory change on atampt last year has had on the 
marketplace 
sikes declined to delay action on the proposed regulatory 
changes both of which could happen before 1991 but he said he 
would make a report to congress on the current state of the 
marketplace 
the petition to the fcc dealt with the commissions order that 
local phone companies on july 1 of this year reduce by 11 billion 
the charges they levied on longdistance carriers to connect with 
local telephone networks 
under the rateofreturn regulation that the fcc abandoned in 
1989 atampt was required to pass on most if not all of its share 
of these savings to customers such actions have been the primary 
reason longdistance prices have declined more than 40 percent 
since 1984 
the price cap regulatory scheme that the fcc adopted in july 
1989 restricts atampts prices instead of its earnings to give it an 
incentive to hold down costs and prices 
atampt doesnt necessarily have to pass through all of the 
access charge reductions to customers in fact atampt boosted 
some small business prices on july 27 
atampts share of the 11 billion access charge reduction was 
about 520 million according to the july 30 issue of business week 
magazine but the companys july 1 prices cuts were just 300 
million 
the petition by the consumer federation of america the 
international communications association and the national 
association of state utility consumer advocates asked the fcc to 
look into the apparent discrepancy of at least 140 million and 
perhaps as much as 200 million 
the groups noting that the fcc had estimated consumers would 
save 900 million over four years under price caps said atampt 
should be required to file data supporting the rate cuts to 
ensure that ratepayers are realizing all of the savings the 
commission promised 
