<TEXT>
president bush envisions needing 500000 fewer 
troops by 1995 in a restructured fastresponse us military but 
he wants to move full speed ahead on major weapons programs 
including the b2 stealth bomber and trident submarine 
bush in a major speech on defense policy in aspen colo on 
thursday said iraqs brutal aggression against kuwait 
demonstrates that the world remains a dangerous place 
even in a world where democracy and freedom have made great 
gains threats remain bush told an aspen institute symposium 
terrorism hostage taking renegade regimes and unpredictable 
rulers all require a strong and engaged america 
on a trip cut short by the iraqi invasion the president 
announced his support for a 25 percent reduction in americas 21 
million active duty military personnel over the next five years 
that would be the lowest level since 1950 
bush said the threat of a sudden soviet invasion of western 
europe was more remote than ever in the postwar period and 
the cold war is now drawing to a close 
with the emergence of democracy in eastern europe the warsaw 
pact has lost its military meaning he said 
an administration official said 200000 of the 1 million 
civilian jobs in the defense department would be cut by the 
mid1990s in addition to the 500000 uniformed positions 
the official who spoke on condition of anonymity also 
predicted that military bases at home and overseas will be 
reduced and restructured dramatically as part of the troop 
reduction 
the possibility of a 25 percent military cut has been raised 
previously by defense secretary dick cheney and gen colin powell 
chairman of the joint chiefs of staff some members of congress 
favor even deeper retrenchment 
what we need are not merely reductions but restructuring 
said bush outlining his vision of a military that would continue 
strategic modernization this would include building all 75 
radarevading b2 bombers and 18 trident missile submarines in his 
defense plan pressing ahead with the mobile midgetman missile and 
putting the silobased mx missile on rails 
bush said a restructured military must be tailored to respond 
rapidly to crises anywhere in the world 
a new emphasis on flexibility and versatility must guide our 
efforts he said these threats can as weve seen just in the 
last 24 hours arise suddenly unpredictably and from unexpected 
quarters 
the events of the past day underscore also the vital need for 
a defense structure which not only preserves our security but 
provides the resources for supporting the legitimate selfdefense 
needs of our friends and allies the president said 
