<DOCNO> AP900803-0040 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
us rep floyd flake and his wife face federal 
charges they embezzled more than 140000 from a 
governmentsubsidized housing project for the elderly and the 
church where flake is pastor 
the indictment unsealed thursday after a twoyear 
investigation prompted denials of any wrongdoing and at least one 
allegation that some black elected officials appear to be targets 
of selective prosecution 
us attorney andrew maloney replied we go wherever the 
evidence takes us 
flake 45 was indicted on 17 counts of conspiracy fraud and 
tax evasion and his wife margarett 42 was indicted on nine 
counts maloney said 
the democrat who represents new yorks predominantly black 6th 
district in queens was charged with diverting 141700 from church 
and housing funds for personal use and failing to report it as 
taxable income 
flake said he had cooperated with the investigation and accused 
the prosecutor of attempting to substitute his judgment on how a 
church should manage its affairs and how a pastor should fulfill 
his special duties 
flakes lawyer gustave h newman said the money was used for 
churchrelated activities and that the case would not affect 
the congressmans plans to seek reelection to a third house term 
in november 
mrs flakes attorney theodore v wells jr said his client 
was added to the indictment simply because she signed joint tax 
returns 
the indictment will give further credence to the perception 
that minority politicians dont get evenhanded treatment wells 
said similar accusations have surfaced recently regarding 
washington mayor marion barry and los angeles mayor tom bradley 
flake is pastor of the allen african methodist church which was 
founded in the 1830s and has a 6000member congregation it built 
the 300unit allen senior citizens apartments in 1981 with a 10 
million federal loan 
the church operates the complex with a 100000 monthly subsidy 
from the department of housing and urban development the 
indictment charged that between 1983 and 1987 the flakes embezzled 
75000 from the complex 
maloney said the money was siphoned from money set aside to 
transport the elderly residents to local stores banks and 
restaurants 
the indictment alleged that flake took another 66700 from a 
special church ministerial expense fund account for his own use 
between 1983 and 1988 
if convicted on all 17 counts flake could be sentenced to a 
maximum of 87 years in prison and fined up to 395 million his 
wife could face penalties of 55 years in prison and fines of up to 
21 million 
the investigation began based on information from sources 
including an alleged paramour of flake maloney said refusing 
to disclose further details 
</TEXT>
