<TEXT>
shelling and gunfire today shook portions of 
kuwaits capital where invading iraqi troops sought to consolidate 
their hold on the persian gulf nation world reaction toughened 
against iraq 
the us aircraft carrier independence headed to the region and 
president bush refused to rule out direct us military 
intervention calling iraqs lightning attack thursday on its 
smaller southern neighbor naked aggression 
france said it planned to send a second warship to the gulf 
world oil prices jumped sharply thursday and us lawmakers 
demanded a worldwide boycott of iraqi oil 
the invasion followed weeks of threats by iraqi president saddam 
hussein in a dispute with kuwait over oil land and money iraq 
threatened to turn the rich sheikdom into a graveyard if anyone 
tried to intervene and said it installed a government to replace 
the emir sheik jaber alahmed alsabah who fled the country 
the 21member arab league scheduled a closed meeting today while 
arab leaders held urgent consultations on how to respond to the 
crisis 
there was no further word on casualties diplomats said at least 
200 kuwaitis were killed or wounded the day before most of them 
from the government emiri guard 
shelling in kuwait city occurred at the countrys main military 
barracks in the northern area of shuwaikh and was heard throughout 
the night indicating resistance was stiffer than the first day of 
the invasion 
there was also artillery shelling on the gulf coast 16 miles 
from shuwaikh and two military vehicles were on fire the 
residents said speaking by phone on condition of anonymity 
a british embassy official quoted by the british news agency 
press association today reported explosions and gunfire along the 
seafront in kuwait city and around key installations including the 
emirs palace 
a curfew was in force all ports were sealed the airport 
remained closed and the three main land crossings into kuwait were 
impassable said the official who spoke on condition of anonymity 
by this afternoon gulfbased diplomats speaking on condition of 
anonymity said the fighting had abated 
telephone operators in the gulf nation of bahrain who previously 
had been able to reach kuwait said this afternoon that lines 
appeared to have been cut off 
the sheiks government vowed to fight to win back the country a 
seemingly impossible task since iraq has 1 million soldiers in its 
army and kuwait has 20000 
his radio station beaming from an unknown location reported 
that the emir was taking charge of directing the resistance from a 
safe place 
meanwhile a spokesman at the us embassy said three americans 
had been seized by the iraqis from the shuaiba oil refinery 
he indicated that the iraqis had taken them to help run the 
refinery and not as any particular threat to the americans 
within kuwait 
the spokesman who could not be named under embassy rules said 
the iraqis were not hostile to americans soldiers escorted 
americans they met on the streets to their homes and were 
treating them very well he said 
nearly 4000 americans are among the large expatriate community 
in kuwait where more than 60 percent of the 19 million residents 
are foreigners iraq has 17 million residents 
iraq recently accused kuwait of stealing oil it claimed its 
troops entered kuwait at the request of revolutionaries who it said 
had staged a coup kuwaiti and other diplomats said the coup report 
was a farce 
iraqi troops backed by 350 tanks and air cover swept into kuwait 
before dawn thursday meeting brave but ultimately ineffective 
resistance from the vastly outnumbered kuwaitis said the 
diplomats speaking on condition of anonymity 
iraqi soldiers were making sweeps today through the southern 
oilfields near saudi arabia according to residents and lloyds 
insurance service in london 
izzat ibrahim deputy chairman of iraqs ruling revolutionary 
command council flew to saudi arabia today on an official visit 
the iraq news agency reported the two oil giants have a 
nonaggression pact 
in the united states members of congress after briefings by 
intelligence officials expressed fears that iraqs next target 
could be saudi arabia 
however a wellinformed diplomatic source in the gulf reported 
no movement of iraqi troops into saudi arabia or directly across 
the iraqsaudi arabian border 
the invasion of kuwait brought universal condemnation and 
sanctions 
the un security council on thursday denounced the occupation 
and demanded that iraq withdraw its troops immediately 
more countries joined the united states in denouncing the 
invasion including south korea new zealand malaysia thailand 
indonesia china singapore 
the soviet union iraqs biggest arms supplier announced a 
suspension of shipments to iraq the united states froze iraqi 
assets and blocked most iraqi imports including its most important 
revenue source oil 
the united states britain and france froze kuwaiti assets 
thursday to protect the holdings from iraqi occupiers japan and 
west germany were among other nations that followed suit today 
officials said 
iraq responded to the american moves by freezing repayment of 
iraqi debts to the united states the official iraqi news agency 
reported the total size of the debt is unclear last year the 
united states provided 1 billion in agricultural credits to iraq 
iraq began threatening kuwait two weeks ago after accusing it of 
stealing oil from a border region claimed by both nations it also 
accused kuwait of depriving it of oil revenues by cheating on opec 
oil cartel production quotas thus driving down oil prices 
talks to resolve the dispute broke down wednesday and diplomats 
said iraq had moved about 100000 soldiers to the kuwait border 
it was unclear whether the takeover would slow or halt kuwaits 
oil production but it seemed to signal an important shift in the 
balance of world oil power 
private analysts said thursday in the united states countries 
dependent on imported oil now face new economic risks the united 
states gets half its oil from abroad 10 percent of which comes 
from iraq and kuwait 
by grabbing control of kuwait saddam added about 94 billion 
barrels of oil reserves to his countrys own 100 billion barrels 
second only to saudi arabia according to the american petroleum 
institute an industry trade group 
iraq larger than california has coveted new jerseysized 
kuwait for decades their common border was left undemarcated upon 
kuwaits independence from britain in 1961 
</TEXT>
