<TEXT>
iraqs capture of kuwaiti oil fields is 
awakening the united states to a shift in the balance of global oil 
power and the prospect of higher prices analysts say 
us dependence on oil from the volatile persian gulf has grown 
rapidly in recent years as american production has fallen that 
leaves the united states increasingly vulnerable to supply 
disruptions and gives the organization of petroleum exporting 
countries more influence over prices 
in 1985 the united states relied on the gulf countries for about 
10 percent of imports this year the gulf share of the american 
market is about 25 percent 
onehalf of all us oil supplies are imported while britain 
and other nonopec oil exporters had snatched part of the american 
market from the middle east producers in the early 1980s some of 
that nonopec supply is drying up 
i dont think the average american has understood how rapidly 
our dependence has increased sen david boren dokla chairman 
of the senate intelligence committee said thursday weve really 
been asleep at the switch in terms of the national security 
implications of relying heavily on middle east oil exporters 
sen lloyd bentsen dtexas called today for new incentives for 
domestic oil production including tax breaks for those who squeeze 
oil from formations now considered unrecoverable 
this weeks news makes our vulnerability more evident and our 
response more urgent said bentsen chairman of the taxwriting 
senate finance committee by failing to learn from this history 
we are condemning ourselves to repeat it 
iraqi president saddam husseins quick strike into kuwait 
highlighted us vulnerability to oil market pressures and to the 
possibility that opec with iraq in a leading role may regain 
its pricefixing clout analysts said 
in a nights work hussein has irrevocably altered not only 
the balance of power in the middle east but the supply and demand 
balance in the world oil market said christopher flavin vice 
president for research at the worldwatch institute in washington 
iraq immediately doubled its share of world oil reserves by 
taking control of kuwait which estimates its reserves at 94 
billion barrels iraq now ranks second in the world to saudi 
arabia which has estimated reserves of 255 billion barrels the 
united states holds 26 billion barrels 
flavin said the bush administration has little prospect for 
stopping iraq from further military conquests in the gulf despite 
the importance of oil to the us economy 
ironically any effort by the united states to directly 
prevent iraqi military action would itself provoke the kind of 
conflict almost certain to disrupt oil supplies and quite possibly 
throw the world into a severe recession flavin said 
with iraq now playing the role of enforcer opec may be in a 
position to tighten world oil supplies over the coming decade 
possibly enabling the cartel to raise its prices and make them 
stick analysts said 
perhaps most troubling for the united states and other large 
oilconsuming nations oil market clout is becoming increasingly 
concentrated in the gulf where no nation has enough military might 
or political leverage to challenge iraqi ambitions 
all of the opec countries at least all of those in the middle 
east will be intimidated by iraq said sen j bennett johnston 
dla chairman of the senate energy and natural resources 
committee iraq will be able to set such prices it wants 
throughout the eight years of the iraniraq war which ended in 
1988 both countries were neutralized on the oil scene leaving 
saudi arabia and kuwait to dominate in opec and ensuring that the 
west would again become hooked on the cartels oil 
after emerging victorious over iran iraq began seeking to 
convert its regional military predominance into added oil clout 
the invasion of kuwait was the first dramatic proof to analysts 
that baghdad is intent on supplanting saudi arabia as the main 
power in opec and leading a drive toward higher oil prices 
