<TEXT>
parliament today elected arpad goencz 
a prominant writer and former political prisoner as president in a 
move that completed the countrys break with its communist past 
goencz had been sentenced to life in prison for his role in the 
1956 anticommunist uprising that was crushed by soviet troops 
all my life i have served and will serve the nations 
independence free thought free speech free ideas and social 
justice goencz told lawmakers after his election i serve 
hungarian democracy 
goencz 68 had been appointed interim president may 2 by the 
newly elected democratic parliament 
todays parliamentary vote came less than a week after the 
failure of a referendum that would have mandated a popular vote for 
the post of president 
goencz is the first president of the republic of hungary which 
was declared last year after the communists agreed to relinquish 
power and compete in multiparty elections 
of 310 deputies present and voting 295 voted for goencz the 
only candidate for the post in a secret ballot there are 386 
deputies in the unicameral legislature 
his election was expected after the failure of the referendum on 
holding a popular vote participation by more than 50 percent of 
the electorate was required for approval but fewer than 14 percent 
went to the polls 
goencz referred indirectly to the failed referendum saying the 
parties who supported him in parliament represented the majority of 
the hungarian people 
thus i can consider myself someone chosen not only by 
parliament but the whole of the people he said in his 
acceptance speech 
the referendum was sponsored by the socialist party heir to the 
now disbanded communist party which has only a small minority in 
parliament 
a referendum victory would have meant a chance for the party to 
regain some of its lost political prestige former premier miklos 
nemeth who ran as an independent in the march parliamentary 
elections still enjoys considerable popularity and observers said 
he would have had a good chance of becoming president in a direct 
election 
in a similar referendum in november hungarians voted 
overwhelmingly in favor of postponing the election of the president 
until after the parliamentary elections that meant the president 
would be elected by parliament the parliamentary elections were 
held march 25 and a runoff on april 8 
goencz who headed the hungarian writers union before his 
election as interim president in may spent six years in jail after 
soviet troops crushed the 1956 revolt against stalinism and rule 
from moscow he won a reprieve on his life sentence under a 1963 
amnesty 
he worked translating britsh and american novels into hungarian 
and eventually published several novels and short stories 
goencz is the third intellectual and former dissident to assume 
an eastern european presidency 
czechoslovak president vaclav havel a prominent playwright was 
jailed and harassed for years before his election in bulgaria on 
wednesday zhelyu zhelev a respected leader of the opposition and 
a man of letters was elected the countrys first noncommunist 
president 
