efforts 
the uncertainties after saddams invasion of kuwait are pushing 
up oil prices but with a big question mark over his ability to 
sell it this may not be a benefit 
it was unclear whether the invasion would slow or halt kuwaits 
oil production iraqi control of kuwaits 94 billion barrels of 
crude oil reserves added to baghdads own 100 billion will be of 
little use to the iraqis if they cannot market their oil 
the war with iran left saddam a foreign debt from 60 billion to 
70 billion including about 30 billion to kuwait saudi arabia 
and other oilrich arab countries that helped finance his war 
a desire to erase part of the debt burden was one reason behind 
saddams sudden invasion 
iraq is saddled with overcentralized state industries and an 
annual inflation rate conservatively estimated at 15 percent 
despite saddams attempts to revitalize the economy by selling 
off 22 billion worth of public companies to private individuals 
and removing some price controls the recovery has been anemic 
using fear as a weapon to push for efficiency saddam has fired 
state officials for inefficiency or corruption but the hopedfor 
economic boom did not materialize 
iraq also announced plans to slash public expenditure and it 
discharged more than 200000 soldiers from the army although with 
the remobilization in the wake of the invasion this saving will be 
eliminated 
iraq relies significantly on financial credits from the west 
baghdad responded to the us sanctions by freezing repayment of 
24 billion in iraqi debts to the united states a move it is 
certain to duplicate against any other countries that block iraqi 
credits 
suspending repayments helps iraq in the short term but in the 
long run cunningham said they have been a net receiver of funds 
not a net payer so the cutoff is sure to hurt 
in addition key western technicians and consultants are likely 
to be ordered out of iraq further crippling the economy 
