<TEXT>
a 65yearold epileptic man stranded in 
the arizona desert survived for nearly three days by eating cactus 
and crawling in search of shade his daughterinlaw said 
manuel cantu of wittmann became so desperate that he tried to 
blow up his disabled car with a gunshot to the gas tank in hopes 
someone would see the fire said diane cantu 
cantu who was reported missing monday was rescued thursday 
after a rancher heard his call for help on a citizens band radio a 
spokesman for the maricopa county sheriffs office said 
he was treated for dehydration and sunburn at phoenix general 
hospital and medical center but was in good condition friday 
family members said 
hes a real cowboy in the truest sense said diane cantu 
hes spent a lot of time in the desert and he knows survival 
skills 
cantu left home monday morning to go target shooting in the 
surrounding desert said his daughterinlaw his car got stuck in 
sand in a deserted area about 30 miles northwest of phoenix where 
temperatures soared well above 100 degrees this week 
cantu has epilepsy and was not carrying medicine but did not 
have a seizure during the ordeal she said 
when his small container of water ran out cantu ripped apart 
cactus and chewed the inside for moisture 
during the day he crawed under palo verde trees which provide 
little shade she said 
diane cantu said her fatherinlaw tried to set a signal fire by 
shooting his cars gasoline tank but the thing wouldnt blow up 
a rescue plane spotted cantus car thursday morning after he 
reached a rancher via his cb radio and the rancher called 
authorities said sheriffs spokesman duane brady 
</TEXT>
