<TEXT>
a 33yearold frenchwoman on friday set a 
record for a solo sailboat crossing of the atlantic ocean french 
media reported 
the woman florence arthaud beat the old best time set by a 
frenchman by nearly two days according to the reports 
ms arthaud arrived at lizard point in southwestern britain in 
the predawn hours after a voyage of nine days 21 hours and 42 
minutes said louis bodin a friend of arthauds who helped guide 
her across the atlantic 
the previous record of 11 days 11 hours and 47 minutes about 
40 hours slower than ms arthauds time was set by bruno peyron 
of france aboard a catamaran in 1987 
im happy ive arrived its the first time im really happy 
its over because it was really tough she said in a french radio 
interview 
its really trying on the nerves to make a crossing like 
that she said i dont get seasick but during the whole trip 
my stomach was tied in knots 
ms arthaud set out from new york city on july 24 aboard the 
60foot trimaran pierre premier 
she averaged a speed of 121 knots or 125 miles per hour over 
the 2800mile route bodin said the crossing would have taken 
less time except there was little wind during the last 80 miles he 
said 
for me the record is no more and no less than a regular 
sailing trip ms arthaud said in a radio interview it wasnt 
routine but its part of my daily life its my life always trying 
to go faster 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900803-0120 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
since march physicians throughout texas 
have reported 149 cases of a mysterious new illness called 
palestine syndrome the malady mostly strikes children and is 
characterized by high fever and temporary arthritis 
dr jeffrey w jundt a physician at scott and white memorial 
hospital who first identified the illness said thursday that 
experts still know little of its origins and are uncertain of how 
or if it can be prevented or cured 
it has not been fatal and victims recover completely jundt 
said but some patients have been hospitalized as long as six 
months 
we have no idea whether its increasing but were not being 
swamped with cases said jeffrey taylor with the texas department 
of health there are some new ones that have onset in july and 
we are following up on those 
the illness was named after a town about midway between dallas 
and houston where it was first encountered last march 
although the ailment is named for palestine so far only four 
confirmed cases have come from there taylor said cases have been 
identified in 34 texas counties most in the north central and 
eastern sections of the state 
scott and white hospital spokeswoman charlene lee said the 
hospital has received inquiries about palestine syndrome from other 
sections of the country the federal centers for disease control 
are investigating but there is no nationwide accounting of how 
many people have the illness 
jundt prefers to call palestine fever the star complex an 
acronym for its major symptoms sore throat temperature greater 
than 100 degrees for seven days arthritis in three different 
joints and a hivelike rash 
symptoms have been reported in 149 people including three 
adults of those 54 cases have been confirmed and 25 of them have 
been recommended for aggressive blood sample studies by the state 
health department and the cdc 
most of the confirmed cases have been in children under age 15 
but some have been in women in their 20s and 30s so far no cases 
have been confirmed in adult males 
the illness does not appear to be contagious 
doctors are testing bodily secretions including saliva urine 
and nasal secretions taken from the 25 patients in hopes of 
isolating viral particles that could help identify other viruses 
that might be associated with the syndrome 
five of the 25 patients in the survey group tested positive for 
the rubella virus and two were positive for parvo virus which is 
commonly associated with puppies but causes arthritis jundt said 
like the progression of the syndrome itself the recovery period 
is variable he said once the virus runs its course recurrent 
episodes are considered unlikely although there have been 
exceptions 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

