<TEXT>
president bushs cutoff of iraqi oil imports 
is costing iraq its no 1 customer but the sanction is unlikely to 
take a lasting toll on baghdad unless japan and other major oil 
importing countries join the embargo 
anything short of a concerted buyer boycott by the oil importing 
nations would be little more than a temporary inconvenience for 
iraq 
a solo american boycott would leave iraq free to sell usbound 
oil to japan or another customer although it might be forced to 
take a slightly lower price in order to move the oil quickly in a 
glutted world market 
but the inconvenience could be felt as much by american oil 
companies as by the iraqi government the embargo announced by bush 
thursday following iraqs invasion of kuwait bars the import of 
iraqi oil but it apparently does not stop american oil companies 
from continuing to buy iraqi oil and ship it to their nonamerican 
affiliates or simply swapping it on the world market 
among the major us oil companies that buy iraqi oil exxon 
corp for example could divert its iraqi purchases to its western 
european affiliates for refining 
the united states among the dozens of countries which condemned 
iraqs takeover of kuwait on friday was the only nation to have 
barred imports of iraqi oil although european governments were 
reported to be considering boycotts 
japans kyodo news service reported tokyo also was contemplating 
a ban 
