<TEXT>
pennsylvanias abortion law is 
constitutionally sound and should be upheld a state attorney said 
thursday in closing arguments on a court challenge to the toughest 
such statute in any state 
an attorney representing a group of abortion clinics and doctors 
opposed to the law countered that its restrictions would strip 
women of dignity potentially endanger their health and have a 
chilling effect on doctors who perform abortions 
there can be no doubt the challenged provisions burden womens 
rights to abortion said thomas zemaitis a lawyer for the 
clinics 
the conflicting assessments came in closing arguments before 
senior us district judge daniel h huyett iii who has been asked 
to overturn key sections of the law on constitutional grounds 
pennsylvanias law is the most stringent on the books of any 
state only guam a us territory in the pacific has adopted more 
stringent controls 
the case has generated national interest because it might 
eventually provide a way to challenge roe vs wade the landmark 
1973 decision that established abortion as a constitutional right 
lawyers expect a ruling in about a month huyett has blocked 
disputed sections of the law until he rules 
among the disputed provisions are requirements that women notify 
their husbands if they want an abortion and wait 24 hours before 
getting an abortion and for minors to obtain the consent of at 
least one parent or a court order before receiving an abortion 
some of the contested sections of the law are redrafted from a 
1982 statute much of which was struck down by the us supreme 
court in 1986 
senior deputy attorney general kate l mershimer argued that 
there had been important abortion rulings since the roe case 
including a july 1989 supreme court decision in webster vs 
reproductive health sercives inc a missouri case that gave states 
greater leeway to restrict abortion 
ms mershimer made a pointbypoint review of each disputed 
section prefacing her remarks by saying we believe our law 
remains constitutional 
zemaitis said testimony had shown how the law would place undue 
restrictions controls that are far out of step with the roe ruling 
he said the provisions hardly promote an interest in womens 
health they harm womens health 
zemaitis said the state was demeaning women by forcing them 
to wait 24 hours for abortions and suggested that the section was 
written simply to discourage abortions 
thats what this provision is all about if we keep women tied 
up 24 hours theyll change their minds he said 
both mershimer and zemaitis have expressed confidence their side 
would win 
most of the witnesses in the trial have been doctors or 
psychologists the trial has been largely devoid of the 
emotionalism and protests that have typified the national debate 
over abortion the courtroom with seating for about 15 was only 
occasionally filled to capacity 
