the state supreme court on thursday upheld 
a ruling that damage lawsuits against boeing co from the 1985 
crash of a boeing 747 owned by japan air lines should be heard by 
japanese courts 
the jal 747sr slammed into a mountainside on a flight from 
tokyo to osaka on aug 12 1985 killing 520 of the 524 people 
aboard 
in 1987 king county superior court judge gary little dismissed 
the claims on condition that boeing submit to jurisdiction in 
japan waive any statuteoflimitations defenses admit liability 
for compensatory damages and accept the judgment on liability in 
japan 
little granted plaintiffs in the case the right to return to 
superior court for trial on damages if the actions cannot be 
handled expeditiously in japan 
the lawsuits were filed against boeing and jal on behalf of the 
estates of 78 victims including 71 japanese citizens 
before dismissing the damage claims the trial court found that 
boeing had admitted botching part of its 1978 repairs on the aft 
pressure bulkhead of the aircraft which separates the pressurized 
section of the plane from tail section boeing admitted its bungled 
repair caused the crash 
attorneys for the plaintiffs appealed on technical grounds and 
argued that dismissal of the damage claims was fundamentally unfair 
the high court confirmed the trial courts finding that the 
plaintiffs would get an adequate hearing in japan 
plaintiffs have not challenged this finding and indeed 
concede that japanese law provides full compensation justice 
barbara durham wrote for the court 
durham said the trial court had found that virtually all of the 
witnesses documents and other evidence pertaining to the issue of 
damages are in japan favoring trial there 
japanese courts tend to provide smaller rewards in damage 
lawsuits 
