hundreds of colombians have died and the 
united states has spent millions of dollars in a yearlong effort 
to destroy the medellin cartel but the war goes on and the cocaine 
still flows north 
a presidential candidate was shot down at a rally the night of 
aug 18 1989 and the government shocked and outraged declared 
war on drug gangs that had become so powerful they threatened to 
take over the country 
luis carlos galan who spoke out against the cocaine barons was 
standing on a wooden platform acknowledging the cheers and applause 
of thousands of people when hired killers opened fire with machine 
guns 
his death began a chain of events that terrorized colombia and 
revealed the horror a voracious us appetite for cocaine could 
create 
a year later the war rages on increasingly it appears 
unwinnable but the government has scored some victories 
national police have seized a record 40 tons of cocaine so far 
this year in raids on jungle laboratories more than the 33 tons 
captured in all of 1989 
cocaine delivered in miami costs 35000 a kilogram or 22 
pounds before last august the price had been as low as 10000 
officials say the higher prices indicate success in reducing the 
supply but the flow has not been stopped 
galans murder awakened colombians from a slumber that had 
permitted drug traffickers free rein president virgilio barco 
issued his declaration of war and the worlds attention focused on 
this south american country 
at the rally the initial reaction to the shots was like the 
response to an earthquake when people know something is terribly 
wrong but do not realize immediately that the ground is heaving 
beneath them 
because of the noisy scene the rapid gunfire made popping 
sounds like small firecrackers not even galans bodyguards 
understood immediately panic and screams began when galan fell 
mortally wounded 
two more presidential candidates were murdered soon afterward 
and the drug gangs bombed a packed airliner killing all 107 people 
aboard in several cities car bombs exploded at restaurants 
supermarkets schools and in the streets 
some bombs in bogota the capital were so powerful they left 
huge clouds hanging over the city of 6 million people 
colombians had viewed terrorism in places like lebanon or israel 
as distant wars among fanatics 
now they had their own terrorists not religious or political 
fanatics with ageold grievances but drug traffickers who killed 
other people coldly to protect their business 
the medellin cartel largest of the cocaine gangs was taking in 
billions of dollars a year by 1989 and warning public officials to 
get out of the way those who couldnt be intimidated were murdered 
we now know that the cartel is like a monstrous octopus in the 
ocean with only the top of its head visible a source involved 
in planning the antidrug war told the associated press the 
tentacles extend to the united states and around the world he 
said referring to bank deposits bribes and murder 
like virtually every other person involved in fighting the 
medellin cartel the source would speak only on condition of 
anonymity 
with galans death and the government crackdown that followed 
the world opened its eyes to the danger of the drug gangs 
president bush sent 65 million worth of military aid to 
colombia from a special fund available to him 
in february he met with the presidents of colombia bolivia and 
peru which provide most of the worlds cocaine in the colombian 
port city of cartagena bush agreed to increase economic aid to the 
impoverished andean nations to help them and their farmers find 
alternate sources of income 
at another summit in britain western european nations 
recognized the high price colombia was paying in the drug war and 
agreed to help 
justice minister roberto salazar noted that other countries were 
realizing the drug trade was international not a colombian problem 
the world began to recognize that colombia is providing 90 
percent of leadership in fighting the drug scourge he said in an 
interview 
because of police raids drug traffickers have moved many 
cocaine processing operations to neighboring brazil and ecuador 
salazar said and the labs being destroyed are so rudimentary they 
can be replaced in a few days 
another problem is the billions of dollars available for bribes 
if a cop in new york or miami making 30000 a year can be 
bribed by drug traffickers there then imagine how easy it is to 
bribe one here who makes only about 2000 an agent of the us 
drug enforcement administration told the ap 
most of the war on traffickers falls to the 80000man national 
police force led by gen miguel gomez 52 who has a university 
degree in education 
fortunately weve got an honest cop at the top a us 
diplomat said 
gomez has dismissed half a dozen colonels several dozen other 
officers and hundreds of ordinary policemen in an effort to clean 
up the force 
a source close to the search for bribe takers said a police 
colonel can make 15000 a month in payoffs 
gomez said he had only 22 helicopters for raiding labs and 
fighting the cocaine gangs and needed 20 more 
salazar the justice minister said the struggle involves much 
more than police or military action 
some countries allow the shipment of cocaineprocessing 
chemicals to colombia he said and the drug lords can buy all the 
weapons they want on the international arms market 
huge arms shipments destined for colombias drug traffickers 
have been seized in the past year but many others obviously get 
through raids on cartel hideouts over the years have turned up 
hundreds of thousands of weapons 
foreign governments appear either unable or unwilling to stop 
the laundering of drug money salazar said in the interview 
industrialized countries must strengthen regulation of banks he 
said and praised us requirements that banks report all accounts 
worth more than 5000 
when they can pick up cellular phones and transfer millions of 
dollars they can own half the world salazar said of the cocaine 
barons 
he said the success of colombias war on the cartels depends in 
large part on how much of their assets are seized elsewhere 
president barcos government negotiated an agreement with the 
united states that allows colombia to share in the hundreds of 
millions of dollars of traffickers assets seized in the united 
states 
cesar gaviria the new president pledged before his 
inauguration aug 7 to press the antidrug war but has said 
colombia will not fight it alone 
gaviria has not indicated whether he will continue barcos 
policy of extraditing trafficking suspects twenty have been sent 
to the united states for trial in the past year but none are 
believed to be major figures 
salazar said colombia must consider reforming its justice system 
so the suspects can be tried at home in the past judges have been 
bribed or coerced into letting drug traffickers go 
drugtrafficking cases should be handled by special judges who 
live and work in protected areas the justice minister said 
</TEXT>
