<TEXT>
for practical everyday purposes the debate 
about whether the economy is in recession or just this side of it 
is all but meaningless 
recession is a technical statistical arbitrary definition it 
isnt a line that when crossed rearranges the perspective any more 
than the autumnal equinox brings a sudden change to fall weather 
for many people it is a rather academic event occurring when 
the economy suffers two consecutive quarters of shrinking gross 
national product and that means you are at least six months into 
it before you know it 
in fact there have been recessions that werent demonstrated 
until they were over and recessions so mild they might have 
represented better times than during some officially designated 
growth periods 
some recessions sneak up gradually as some economists believe 
is happening now and others explode as in 1973 when president 
ford was campaigning to whip inflation now not realizing that 
a deep recession had begun 
there have been recessions that skipped some geographical and 
occupational areas and a recession in the mid1980s that 
encompassed most of the nation but never qualified as one because 
good times in a few states skewed the averages 
at one extreme there have been recessions so deep unemployment 
rose to 25 percent and so long they ruined most of a decade as in 
the late unlamented 1930s and at the other extreme recessions 
that came and departed silently 
far more important than the technical definitions are 1 the 
strength or weakness of the economy and 2 whether it is gaining 
strength or losing it right now the economy is weak and it is 
losing strength 
real gross national product rose at an annual rate of just 12 
percent during the second quarter of the year the fifth straight 
quarter of less than 2 percent growth rates a healthy economy 
would grow twice as fast 
for probably the only time since the recession of the early 
1980s the major private sectors of the economy consumer 
spending business fixed investment housing construction and net 
exports declined simultaneously 
in the same quarter real disposable personal income rose at an 
anemic annual rate of less than 1 percent consumer confidence is 
unsteady big ticket sales are off some housing values are down 
homebuilding is depressed 
some perhaps most of this is a consequence of what is called 
the federal reserves tight money policy restrict the flow of 
money to the economy and the price of it interest rates goes up 
or remains high 
tight money means tougher borrowing conditions the intent of 
which is to suppress activity in real estate for example easy 
money policies of the mid1980s had led to bad loans an excess of 
construction and bankruptcies 
tight money however is a blunt instrument hurting bad risks 
and good together it is the weapon now being used by the fed to 
bring down what are seen as inflationary pressures but it could 
create new ones 
small business for example is complaining that it is bearing 
the brunt of the slowdown effort and a survey by the us chamber 
of commerce tends to confirm that claim 
the survey found that 20 percent of all businesses seeking 
credit in the past six months had trouble borrowing but that for 
smaller commpanies those with sales of less than 1 million the 
percentage rose to 274 
small companies are generally the innovators and job creators 
they are the price cutters they are risktakers capable of 
failing to be sure but also of growing swiftly they are the 
future competition for giant companies 
for them the source of future economic growth the recession 
has already begun no matter that the official declaration of 
recession has not been made 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

