the surplus in the broadest measure of japans 
trade rose 122 percent in june from a year earlier snapping two 
consecutive months of decline the finance ministry said friday 
the surplus in the current account the widest measure of a 
nations trade in goods and services widened to 478 billion from 
426 billion in june 1989 according to the ministry 
the june increase followed a 575 percent decline in the current 
account in may on a yearonyear basis in may the surplus stood 
at 146 billion 
finance ministry officials attributed the rise in the current 
account surplus to higher exports and a decline in oil prices but 
they added that it was too early to determine whether the downward 
trend had fully reversed 
the merchandise trade surplus for june rose 80 percent from a 
year earlier to 705 billion on an unadjusted basis 
exports rose for the first time in nine months increasing 33 
percent to 2310 billion imports rose to 1605 billion up 14 
percent from a year earlier 
exports and imports in the current account are measured when 
contracts are settled and are different from the customsclearance 
trade figures which are announced separately by the ministry each 
month the current account does not include breakdowns of trade 
figures by country or region 
 
