<TEXT>
accountants without a license can practice 
in california but have to call themselves unlicensed 
accountants according to a state appeals court ruling released 
thursday 
in a 30 decision the 1st district court of appeal upheld the 
state board of accountancys authority to allow only californias 
55000 certified public accountants to use the terms accountant 
or accounting without other modification in connection with 
their business 
but the court noted that state law does not require a license to 
prepare financial reports or do most other accounting work 
certified public accountants who must meet state standards for 
education and experience and pass a national examination can 
certify their audits and financial statements to lenders 
government agencies stockholders and the public 
people without licenses can call themselves accountants the 
court said as long as they also state that they are unlicensed or 
provide some other disclaimer saying their services do not require 
a license 
because the constitution provides some protection to free speech 
in advertising we must permit the use of those terms such as 
accountant if they are qualified by a warning or disclaimer that 
avoids their misleading impact said the opinion by presiding 
justice clinton white 
the ruling is a partial victory but is far from satisfactory 
said ralph alldredge a lawyer for the california association of 
independent accountants a group of about 700 unlicensed 
accountants he said no decision has been made yet on an appeal 
to call yourself an unlicensed accountant is a derogatory 
term almost he said its a very negative way to have to 
present yourself to the public 
alldredge said no one knows how many unlicensed accountants work 
in california because of state restrictions he said some list 
themselves in telephone directories under bookkeeping or tax 
services or business consulting none of which accurately describes 
their work 
the association he represents joined bonnie moore an unlicensed 
san francisco accountant with a college degree in accounting in a 
1986 suit challenging the state board of accountancys regulations 
the board had ordered moore and her firm to stop using the terms 
accounting and accountant in their business san francisco 
superior court judge thomas dandurand ruled in the boards favor 
white noted that the us supreme court has recognized 
advertisers right to free expression in truthful claims those 
rulings indicate that practitioners such as moore must be allowed 
to tell the public they are accountants as long as they specify 
that they do not have or need a license for their work white said 
</TEXT>
