<TEXT>
recession fears inflation worries and conflicting reports from 
the persian gulf ricocheted through us commodity markets friday 
resulting in price moves with little relation to supply and demand 
factors 
it seemed like a lot of attention was focused on what the 
latest rumors were observed tim evans a copper trader with deak 
international inc a new yorkbased dealer of metals and 
currencies 
oil futures ended sharply higher despite active selling late in 
the session precious metals were higher copper futures fell 
livestock and meat were mixed and grains and soybeans were mixed 
commodity traders kept close watch on stock and crudeoil 
markets where changing news reports about the iraqkuwait 
situation caused wild price swings that rippled out to other 
markets 
war is always bearish for stocks and bullish for 
commodities said victor lespinasse an assistant vice president 
in the graintrading division of dean witter reynolds inc in 
chicago 
the persian gulf situation seemed very bullish for commodities 
early in the day when rumors circulated that iraqi troops had 
invaded saudi arabia from kuwait which probably would result in 
further disruptions of crude oil shipments to the united states 
those rumors were discounted but news reports then surfaced that 
iraqi troops were just six miles from the saudi border causing 
another plunge in stock prices and sharp gains in many commodities 
newswires then reported iraq had told the soviet union it 
planned to withdraw from kuwait prompting a strong rally on the 
stock market and selling in the commodity markets particularly in 
crude oil 
after most market had closed reports came out that the iraqi 
government would begin withdrawing troops from kuwait on sunday 
to further complicate matters the labor department reported 
friday that nonfarm payroll employment fell by 219000 in july and 
unemployment jumped threetenths of a percentage point to 55 
percent 
the figures reinforced concern in the financial world that 
economic activity was weakening more than had been thought just a 
few weeks ago 
the recession fears weighed heavily on the copper market which 
is especially sensitive to signs of economic weakness and on the 
stock market the dow jones industrial average fell more than 120 
points early in the afternoon but recovered to finish with a loss 
of about 55 points 
a similar plunge in stockindex futures prices tripped two 
circuitbreakers in the standard amp poors 500 index futures 
trading pit at the chicago mercantile exchange the circuit 
breakers are a series of trading halts and price limits intended to 
stop a runaway stockmarket collapse 
the contract for september delivery of the 500 stocks tracked by 
the index settled 662 points lower at 34486 the contract is 
valued at 500 a point 
copper futures settled 24 cents to 34 cents lower on new 
yorks commodity exchange with the contract for delivery in august 
at 1261 a pound 
