<TEXT>
allegheny international inc said friday 
federal bankruptcy court had approved of an agreement giving a new 
york investment group control of the maker of sunbeam and oster 
appliances 
the company also announced 321 million in losses in its fiscal 
1990 third quarter as consumerproducts divisions posted decreased 
operating earnings 
the us bankruptcy court approval will allow the investors 
japonica partners to take control of allegheny on aug 15 the 
deal announced thursday by committees representing company 
creditors and shareholders is contingent on japonicas ability to 
raise enough money 
alleghenys senior managers and board members would be ousted on 
that date by japonicas handpicked managers and a board comprising 
nominees from allegheny bank creditors and unsecured creditors 
the executive committee of allegheny internationals board of 
directors which had opposed japonicas assuming a position of 
power unanimously approved the settlement thursday the full board 
ratified the deal friday 
allegheny international filed for protection from creditors 
under chapter 11 of federal bankruptcy laws in february 1988 
the company to be renamed sunbeamoster companies inc 
initially will remain a publicly traded company but japonica is 
expected to own 90 percent of the stock creditors lawyers said at 
a bankruptcy court hearing 
japonica has said it intends to keep company headquarters in 
pittsburgh where allegheny international employs about 60 people 
the agreement would distribute stock and warrants to creditors 
and shareholders as specified in managements reorganization plan 
but would require japonica to buy the securities from anyone who 
wants to sell 
the price would be 7 per share or 153 per warrant except for 
bank creditors who have agreed to accept 660 per share 
creditors would have the option of keeping their stock 
japonica would combine about 270 million in cash allegheny 
international has on hand with 97 million in equity it has 
received from its primary investors to repay the companys bank 
lenders and trade creditors of the companys operating units 
japonica also would have to provide 100 million in working 
capital for the companys operations and a 10 million letter of 
credit to fund administrative expenses incurred after aug 15 
the group also would have to honor severance agreements for 
allegheny internationals senior managers which would cost 53 
million 
japonica already has invested about 125 million to buy claims 
against allegheny international entitling it to receive about half 
of the reorganized companys stock 
japonica has said it intends to appoint william webber who ran 
the sunbeam unit in the early 1980s president of the reorganized 
company 
