<DOCNO> AP900803-0221 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a federal appeals court ruled friday that 
an agency created by congress to protect securities investors can 
sue fraudulent brokers for racketeering and seek triple damages 
the 9th us circuit court of appeals said the securities 
investor protection corp can use the powerful racketeer 
influenced and corrupt organizations act in civil suits against 
brokers 
sipc reimburses customers of failed brokers and can appoint a 
receiver to sell or liquidate an insolvent broker who has violated 
the law if the brokers assets are not enough to pay claims sipc 
uses its own funds collected from member institutions 
the agency moved in 1981 to liquidate two brokerages first 
state securities corp and joseph sebag inc and said it had to 
spend nearly 13 million of its own funds to pay customer claims 
sipc then sued in federal court in los angeles against six 
companies and numerous individuals claiming they had used the two 
brokers as vehicles to manipulate the companies stock in the 
overthecounter market 
the lawsuit sought triple damages under rico claiming that the 
stock fraud had been a pattern of racketeering activity 
a federal district judge dismissed the racketeering claim 
saying sipc had neither bought nor sold the securities in question 
as required for a stock fraud suit but the appeals court said rico 
suits are not limited to buyers or sellers of stock 
noting that the rico law expressly covers any person injured 
in his business or property by reason of a violation the court 
said the law made no reference to a requirement that a plaintiff be 
a buyer or seller of securities 
it is not appropriate for this court to impose such a 
limitation judge david thompson said in the 30 ruling 
reinstating the rico claim 
lawyers for both sides in the case said the ruling appeared 
broad enough to apply to some defrauded private investors as well 
people who werent buyers or sellers of stock which was the 
subject of manipulation could come in under rico if they had 
suffered losses said stephen taylor a lawyer for sipc 
i think it is a broadening of the law and would have wide 
implications beyond sipc said jack mamet a lawyer for defendant 
robert g holmes jr the founder and president of aero systems 
inc one of the six companies whose stock was allegedly 
manipulated 
mamet said a supreme court appeal would be considered 
depending on the rulings interpretation mamet said an 
investor in a future case who held stock affected by fraud but who 
had not been induced to buy or sell the stock because of the fraud 
could be able to sue under rico 
sipc is a nonprofit corporation whose membership consists of 
most registered brokers and dealers it was established in 1970 
after the collapse of several brokerage houses 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

